# Jongara Dart/Flutter Coding Standards

## General Guidelines
- Follow the official [Dart style guide](https://dart.dev/guides/language/effective-dart/style)
- Use meaningful variable and function names
- Keep functions small and focused on a single responsibility
- Document public APIs with dartdoc comments

## Flutter-Specific Guidelines
- Prefer composition over inheritance for widget creation
- Extract reusable widgets into separate files
- Use const constructors whenever possible
- Implement proper error handling throughout the application

## State Management
- Use setState for simple state management
- No external state management libraries (Riverpod, Provider, BLoC)
- Keep state management simple and contained within widgets

## File Organization
- One class per file for major components
- Group related smaller widgets in a single file when appropriate
- Follow the established directory structure

## Naming Conventions
- **Files**: snake_case (e.g., `mahjong_tile.dart`)
- **Classes**: PascalCase (e.g., `MahjongTile`)
- **Variables/Functions**: camelCase (e.g., `tilePosition`)
- **Constants**: camelCase or SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE for truly static values

## Code Structure
- Organize class members in a logical order:
  1. Static properties and methods
  2. Instance properties
  3. Constructors
  4. Public methods
  5. Private methods
- Use regions/sections with comments to organize large files

## Performance Considerations
- Minimize widget rebuilds
- Use const constructors for immutable widgets
- Implement proper list view optimization for scrolling components
- Consider memory usage when handling game state

## Testing
- Write unit tests for core game logic
- Implement widget tests for UI components
- Use integration tests for critical user flows